  == Exploratory Data Analysis
  <exploratory-data-analysis>
  I started by examining the response variable. Before choosing a model,
  it is important to understand whether or not global sales are roughly
  symmetric.
  
  #Skylighting(([#NormalTok("plt.figure(figsize");#OperatorTok("=");#NormalTok("(");#DecValTok("7");#NormalTok(", ");#DecValTok("5");#NormalTok("))");],
  [#NormalTok("plt.hist(games[");#StringTok("\"Global_Sales\"");#NormalTok("], bins");#OperatorTok("=");#DecValTok("40");#NormalTok(")");],
  [#NormalTok("plt.xlabel(");#StringTok("\"Global Sales (millions)\"");#NormalTok(")");],
  [#NormalTok("plt.ylabel(");#StringTok("\"Number of Games\"");#NormalTok(")");],
  [#NormalTok("plt.title(");#StringTok("\"Distribution of Global Video Game Sales\"");#NormalTok(")");],
  [#NormalTok("plt.show()");],));
  #box(image("./media-2530178f772720ff/index_files/figure-pdf/cell-6-output-1.pdf"))
  
  Global sales are heavily right-skewed. Most games sell relatively few
  copies, while a small number of blockbuster games sell far more than the
  rest of the dataset. Because of this, I created a log-transformed
  version of global sales for modeling.
  
  #Skylighting(([#NormalTok("games[");#StringTok("\"Log_Global_Sales\"");#NormalTok("] ");#OperatorTok("=");#NormalTok(" np.log1p(games[");#StringTok("\"Global_Sales\"");#NormalTok("])");],
